1
00:00:22,900 --> 00:00:24,700
For my daughter MingXia

2
00:00:28,300 --> 00:00:30,800
London, 2:30 PM

3
00:00:40,900 --> 00:00:42,300
Hi, Mom.

4
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:46,600
Hi, dear. I have bad news.
Your dad's prognosis isn't good.

5
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:50,300
You have to come.
-Did he ask you to call?

6
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:52,900
Not in so many words.

7
00:00:53,100 --> 00:00:57,300
We saw each other for 15 minutes last summer.
You were there, we had nothing to say as usual.

8
00:00:57,500 --> 00:01:01,700
Sebastien, with his flat, bank account,
insurance, the university...

9
00:01:01,900 --> 00:01:04,800
Your sister's in Australia.
I'm all alone, it's too much for me.

10
00:01:06,600 --> 00:01:08,500
I'll see if Gaelle can come.

11
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:27,400
Hi, love.

12
00:01:28,900 --> 00:01:31,000
He's worse?
-I have to be there.

13
00:01:31,300 --> 00:01:34,500
I'll come.

14
00:01:54,500 --> 00:01:57,800
THE BARBARIAN INVASIONS

15
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:09,400
The body of Christ.

16
00:03:35,500 --> 00:03:37,800
The body of Christ.

17
00:03:38,100 --> 00:03:40,100
The communion's for me.

18
00:03:40,300 --> 00:03:42,900
The body of Christ.

19
00:03:47,700 --> 00:03:52,300
How's Mr Desmarais?
-I don't know. I'm not Mr Desmarais.

20
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:55,800
Sorry,
the computer system is a mess.

21
00:03:56,100 --> 00:03:58,400
Constance Lazure.
- My wife Louise.

22
00:03:58,700 --> 00:04:00,400
Must be hard having him here.

23
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:03,300
I threw him out 15 years ago.

24
00:04:03,400 --> 00:04:06,700
So whether he's here
or humping co-eds in his condo...

25
00:04:06,900 --> 00:04:10,900
Gimme a break. You know it's been
years since I "humped" a co-ed.

26
00:04:11,100 --> 00:04:16,000
And Raphaelle Metellus?
-She was Dominique and Pierre's student.

27
00:04:16,300 --> 00:04:20,700
You were her private tutor? "Kneel down,
 open wide so that I don't feel your teeth."

28
00:04:22,600 --> 00:04:27,100
I'd best continue my rounds. Have a good day!
-You too, Sister.

29
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:31,000
I called Sebastien to let him know.

30
00:04:31,100 --> 00:04:34,500
You did?
-Aren't you glad?

31
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:38,000
Lovely, we can play his video games.
-He's still young.

32
00:04:38,300 --> 00:04:43,300
Ok, but couldn't he have read
one book in his life?

33
00:04:43,700 --> 00:04:45,400
Any book? Is that asking too much?

34
00:04:45,600 --> 00:04:50,100
He may not read, but he earns
more in a month than you earn in a year.

35
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,500
Thanks a lot.
-That's ok, we had room.

36
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:04,000
It's flying to Belfast Monday...
-I'll probably have to stay longer.

37
00:05:05,700 --> 00:05:07,900
My darling!

38
00:05:09,700 --> 00:05:14,200
You must be exhausted.
What time is it for you? 2 a.m.?

39
00:05:14,600 --> 00:05:17,900
Gaelle, how are you, dear?
-Fine, thank you.

40
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:26,600
Hello, sir.
-Young man.

41
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:31,500
Do you remember Gaelle?
-Gaelle is unforgettable.

42
00:05:35,500 --> 00:05:37,300
How are you?

43
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:48,900
No private rooms?
-I'm lucky I'm not in the hall.

44
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:51,600
I tried, all I got was voice mail.

45
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,800
<i>Dad's very sick.
Please get in touch.</i>

46
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:08,900
What I see isn't encouraging.

47
00:06:10,800 --> 00:06:13,400
But to be sure I need a PET scan.

48
00:06:17,800 --> 00:06:20,300
See if they can do it.
They can send it by satellite.

49
00:06:21,600 --> 00:06:24,600
It stands for
Positron Emission Tomography.

50
00:06:24,900 --> 00:06:29,600
Sherbrooke has one, but
there's a 6-12 month waiting list.

51
00:06:30,100 --> 00:06:33,200
Isn't he going to Burlington today?
They have one, -

52
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:37,200
but it's expensive. $2000 U.S.
You'll have to pay cash or by credit card.

53
00:06:37,300 --> 00:06:40,100
Money's no problem.
-You're lucky.

54
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:44,700
You never listened to my body.

55
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:48,600
But I'm not laying a guilt.
-Look, I have to get dressed.

56
00:06:48,800 --> 00:06:54,100
An ambulance is taking me to Burlington in 10 minutes.
-No more excuses!

57
00:06:54,300 --> 00:06:56,700
For my radiation therapy.
-No!

58
00:06:56,900 --> 00:07:01,800
The machines here are too old.
-Stop avoiding me.

59
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:05,700
This is my son, Sebastien,
he's going with me.

60
00:07:15,700 --> 00:07:19,600
She's a woman I used to know, long ago.

61
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:27,700
I couldn't face coming alone.

62
00:07:27,900 --> 00:07:30,300
You've never been here?
-Never.

63
00:07:31,100 --> 00:07:33,700
But you see each other regularly.

64
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:38,300
Always on neutral ground.
Usually in restaurants.

65
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:42,500
Did he come to your place?
-Occasionally.

66
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:46,000
But you never came here.

67
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:50,500
No. I knew that this was where he
brought his mistresses.

68
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:54,100
If we're lucky, we'll find some little panties.

69
00:07:58,100 --> 00:08:01,100
I'm glad Sebastien's going with him today.

70
00:08:01,300 --> 00:08:03,300
It's important they talk, those two.

71
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:24,300
[Playing "America, The Beautiful"]

72
00:08:56,400 --> 00:09:00,300
You know the saying, "Christmas in the scanner,
Easter 6 feet under."

73
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:13,100
I have the scan.

74
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:17,100
It doesen't look good.
Not good at all.

75
00:09:22,100 --> 00:09:27,600
We can't be certain,
but the margin of error is almost nil.

76
00:09:30,400 --> 00:09:32,400
<i>Is he in a lot of pain?</i>

77
00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:41,200
Why don't you bring him here?
At least he wouldn't suffer.

78
00:09:41,500 --> 00:09:44,900
<i>We'll make sure of it.</i>

79
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:48,600
I'm sorry, buddy.

80
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:04,200
Baltimore's not far.
7 hours by car, an hour by plane.

81
00:10:04,500 --> 00:10:08,700
I won't go into EXILE.
-Wouldn't you like your own room-

82
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,200
with a bathroom, CDs?
-What CDs?

83
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:17,700
So you can listen to music.
They have that in civilized countries. AC too.

84
00:10:17,900 --> 00:10:20,700
Know what that costs?
-Nothing. I'll take care of it.

85
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,700
I won't know a soul.
-We'll all go tomorrow.

86
00:10:23,900 --> 00:10:29,700
No we won't. I'm not going to the States,
I don't feel like being murderd by raging idots!

87
00:10:30,300 --> 00:10:35,500
I voted for Medicare, I'll accept the consequences.
-Only idiots refuse to change.

88
00:10:35,700 --> 00:10:39,100
I want to be with my friends.
-Your friends? Where are they?

89
00:10:39,300 --> 00:10:40,900
Dominique's away, but Pierre...

90
00:10:41,100 --> 00:10:44,700
Meanwhile you've got no one.
Apart from that lunatic this morning.

91
00:10:44,900 --> 00:10:46,800
Which lunatic?
-It's irrelevant.

92
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:49,500
The tears, rolling eyes: My Remy!

93
00:10:49,700 --> 00:10:52,400
Who's he talking about?
-Marlene Dupire.

94
00:10:52,700 --> 00:10:57,300
You didn't sleep with Marlene Dupire?
She's a certified nut, everyone knows!

95
00:10:57,500 --> 00:11:01,500
You wrecked your family for her kind?
-I wrecked nothing!

96
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:04,900
You ruined Mom's life,
my adolescence, Sylvaine's...

97
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:07,000
Blaming me for her failure?

98
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:14,100
She loves the sea, she sails the world,
delivering yachts. Beats a 3rd-rate university.

99
00:11:14,200 --> 00:11:17,400
You may be a millionaire,
but you know nothing!

100
00:11:17,700 --> 00:11:21,700
I know I won't end up like you!
She's the reason I'm here.

101
00:11:21,900 --> 00:11:24,900
She raised me, not you!

102
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:28,500
Don't you have a plane
to catch to Hong Kong?

103
00:11:28,800 --> 00:11:32,200
I don't need you, not for one second!
Go to hell!

104
00:11:32,500 --> 00:11:35,300
Fuck you!
-Go to hell!

105
00:12:45,400 --> 00:12:48,500
We're going back to London.
-You can't.

106
00:12:48,700 --> 00:12:51,300
We offer him the best hospital in the world,
he refuses.

107
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:53,900
You heard him. He'll never change.

108
00:12:54,500 --> 00:12:58,300
You plan to have kids?
-Definitely.

109
00:12:58,800 --> 00:13:02,000
Until you're a parent
you'll never understand.

110
00:13:02,500 --> 00:13:05,300
He changed your diapers.

111
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:08,500
He called your teachers every month
all through school.

112
00:13:08,700 --> 00:13:11,700
He so wanted you to do well.

113
00:13:12,900 --> 00:13:15,500
When you had meningitis at age 3,

114
00:13:15,700 --> 00:13:20,300
he rocked you in his arms
for 48 hours non-stop,

115
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:22,700
without sleep,
to keep death at bay.

116
00:13:24,100 --> 00:13:26,100
You can't remember that.

117
00:13:31,600 --> 00:13:33,700
What should I do?

118
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:38,200
Find his friends.
Find him a comfortable room.

119
00:13:38,600 --> 00:13:40,600
That shouldn't be hard.

120
00:13:43,900 --> 00:13:49,500
The Ministry forbids changing hospitals.
Anyway, they'd park him in the hall in Emergency.

121
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:52,800
The floor below is empty?
-2 years, now.

122
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,000
Could he move there?
-Ice cream with your pie?

123
00:13:56,200 --> 00:13:59,500
You can always ask at Administration.
Good luck!

124
00:14:04,600 --> 00:14:06,100
I'll leave you now.

125
00:14:06,300 --> 00:14:09,800
You know, you're lucky to have such a caring son.
-You think so?

126
00:14:10,300 --> 00:14:13,700
How many children  come here?

127
00:14:14,200 --> 00:14:17,800
Look around! See many children at their parent's 
bedside? I'm here every day, so I know.

128
00:14:18,100 --> 00:14:20,400
I never see mine.

129
00:14:20,900 --> 00:14:24,600
Did you have a father?
Was he ever hospitalized?

130
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:27,500
In the end.
-Did you visit him often?

131
00:14:27,700 --> 00:14:30,600
He lived in Chicoutimi, I was teaching 
in Montreal, and it was winter.. so...

132
00:14:30,800 --> 00:14:33,000
You came from England?

133
00:14:33,200 --> 00:14:37,200
London, Chicoutimi, for you...
same thing? Cancer has made you a bit confused?

134
00:14:42,100 --> 00:14:44,900
When it's over, press End.
That stops it.

135
00:14:45,100 --> 00:14:48,100
It's hard, but if you concentrate,
you'll manage.

136
00:14:50,100 --> 00:14:53,700
<i>Hi, Dad!
See, the Pacific Ocean.</i>

137
00:14:54,300 --> 00:14:57,600
<i>We're sailing from Sydney
to New Caledonia,</i>

138
00:14:57,800 --> 00:15:01,300
<i>on to Easter Island
and finally Valparaiso.</i>

139
00:15:02,900 --> 00:15:07,800
<i>I'm sending you lots of sea air.
They say it's good for your health.</i>

140
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:13,600
<i>I have to go. Satellite connections
cost a fortune.</i>

141
00:15:15,100 --> 00:15:19,000
<i>I'm sending you lots and lots of kisses.
Bye for now!</i>

142
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:09,800
Security badge?
-Ms Pelletier? Lloyd's of London.

143
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,700
Didn't they give you one?
-No.

144
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:23,600
Last door on the right.
But next time you need a badge.

145
00:16:28,900 --> 00:16:32,100
Hello.
Pauline Joncas-Pelletier.

146
00:16:32,200 --> 00:16:34,100
Please have a seat.

147
00:16:36,700 --> 00:16:40,600
Well now, my assistant has informed me that you 
represent Lloyd's of London?

148
00:16:41,100 --> 00:16:43,500
Nope, not at all, I said that just to get in.

149
00:16:43,700 --> 00:16:47,800
My father's here on the 3rd floor.
I'd like to move him to the empty floor.

150
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:51,000
Set up something more comfortable.

151
00:16:52,900 --> 00:16:54,900
That's wonderful!

152
00:16:55,100 --> 00:17:00,500
[Snobby] Indead that complies perfectly with our awareness
programs involving family members.

153
00:17:00,700 --> 00:17:05,400
But unfortunately our allocation
of infrastructure is determined

154
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:07,900
by the Ministry's ambulatory thrust.

155
00:17:08,200 --> 00:17:13,000
It's absolutely impossible to target our
responses in terms of individual beneficiaries.

156
00:17:13,900 --> 00:17:17,400
I'm sure our personel...
-I prepared this file.

157
00:17:18,800 --> 00:17:24,300
You must understand, our resource allocation
aims at prioritizing responses

158
00:17:24,600 --> 00:17:29,400
according to diagnostic parameters
defined by the Region 02 consultations.

159
00:17:38,900 --> 00:17:42,500
Eh, seriously.
Even still, we're not quite in Third World.

160
00:17:42,700 --> 00:17:44,300
Think it over.

161
00:17:44,600 --> 00:17:49,400
[Snobby] Even if we close our eyes, we'd require
union integration and cooperation.

162
00:17:49,600 --> 00:17:52,500
And that is a problematic!
-I'll handle them.

163
00:17:52,700 --> 00:17:57,200
This file will be updated weekly.
I'll come back tomorrow. Thank you!

164
00:17:57,900 --> 00:18:04,200
There's a room on the empty floor.
It'll take 5 minutes. I just want to show you.

165
00:18:04,900 --> 00:18:06,900
I'll be back in 5.

166
00:18:12,300 --> 00:18:14,300
Sorry, take the next one.

167
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:23,100
I want to set up a room on this floor.
We could...

168
00:18:23,300 --> 00:18:26,900
Look, nothing happens
without the union.

169
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:33,500
Nothing starts or ends without the union. Clear?
-Why do you think I came to you...

170
00:18:37,200 --> 00:18:40,800
You'd have to paint it,
scrub the floor...

171
00:18:41,700 --> 00:18:45,700
Just a sec, man. Maybe you don' realize...

172
00:18:46,300 --> 00:18:50,900
You're talking overtime, you realize.
And my guys don't... -Paid in cash.

173
00:18:51,100 --> 00:18:54,400
Cash?
-Cash. One painter.

174
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:56,400
Two.

175
00:18:56,900 --> 00:18:58,700
Six hours.

176
00:18:58,900 --> 00:19:00,500
Eight.

177
00:19:00,700 --> 00:19:02,700
What's the rate?

178
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:05,700
$40.
-$35.

179
00:19:05,900 --> 00:19:10,900
I want a bed, curtains, chairs...
-Look, man, that's not us who does that.

180
00:19:11,100 --> 00:19:16,500
You hire a crew, supervise the work.
And charge me reasonable admistration fees.

181
00:19:16,749 --> 00:19:19,821
Reasonable?
-Under 19%

182
00:19:19,900 --> 00:19:23,800
Here's $2500 for starters.
We'll settle up every 2 days.

183
00:19:33,800 --> 00:19:35,500
Where's my laptop?

184
00:19:35,700 --> 00:19:37,400
What?
-My computer.

185
00:19:37,600 --> 00:19:39,800
On the floor.
-It's not there.

186
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:42,800
It must be.
-Nothing there.

187
00:19:43,600 --> 00:19:47,400
The floor, not the locker.
I'm not crazy. -It's not there.

188
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:49,500
Someone must have taken it.

189
00:19:49,700 --> 00:19:51,300
Who?
-I don't know.

190
00:19:51,500 --> 00:19:54,800
It seems like you don't get it. I've had 
50 emails since yesterday. How'll I recover them?

191
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:58,700
My entire deal with Norway.
I didn't have a backup. I was in the middle of doing it..

192
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:02,200
Do you even know what I do?
-No. I would know if you had ever explained it.

193
00:20:02,400 --> 00:20:04,900
Why bother? You never listen!

194
00:20:11,800 --> 00:20:16,300
<i>There were, what, 3000 dead.
Historically, that's insignificant.</i>

195
00:20:16,500 --> 00:20:18,500
<i>As a U.S. example,</i>

196
00:20:18,700 --> 00:20:21,000
<i>50,000 died
at the Battle of Gettysburg.</i>

197
00:20:21,200 --> 00:20:29,600
<i>What is significant,
as my old prof said,</i>

198
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,200
<i>is they struck at
the heart of the Empire.</i>

199
00:20:33,400 --> 00:20:36,100
<i>In previous conflicts- Korea,
Vietnam, the Gulf War</i>

200
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:41,900
<i>the Empire managed to keep the barbarians
outside its gates, its borders</i>

201
00:20:42,400 --> 00:20:49,400
<i>In that sense, people may look back on 9/11,
and I stress may,</i>

202
00:20:49,800 --> 00:20:53,800
<i>as the beginning
of the great barbarian invasions.</i>

203
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:56,500
<i>Alain Lussier, thank you.</i>
<i>-My pleasure.</i>

204
00:21:00,200 --> 00:21:06,300
Excuse me, my computer was just stolen.
-Oh yeah? Fill out this form.

205
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:11,200
What for?
-It's for the police.

206
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:14,100
Look, I've had all these
since Monday.

207
00:21:14,300 --> 00:21:19,700
The police ever investigate?
-No, only when there's physical violence.

208
00:21:19,900 --> 00:21:24,800
Last week a woman was raped in the
old laundry room, so then they came.

209
00:21:24,900 --> 00:21:27,700
Otherwise they'd be here 24/7.

210
00:21:27,800 --> 00:21:30,900
It's easy to rob patients.
Their eyes are closed half the time.

211
00:21:32,300 --> 00:21:35,300
And the union protects the employees.

212
00:21:35,700 --> 00:21:37,500
There's not much we can do.

213
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:44,500
Ronald?

214
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:51,600
What can I do for you, pal?
-I lost or misplaced my computer.

215
00:21:51,800 --> 00:21:57,800
Maybe in my dad's room. So, on the off-chance
someone should find a laptop somewhere...

216
00:21:58,900 --> 00:22:03,200
We'll ask around,
but I can't guarantee anything.

217
00:22:03,400 --> 00:22:06,600
In case.
-Right, in case. We'll check.

218
00:22:07,500 --> 00:22:09,400
Thanks, I appreciate it.

219
00:22:16,100 --> 00:22:19,400
Hello? Speaking.

220
00:22:22,100 --> 00:22:24,500
Of course I remember you, Sebastien.

221
00:22:24,700 --> 00:22:26,900
How are you?

222
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:29,700
Yes, it's been a long time.

223
00:22:35,900 --> 00:22:37,900
He's very sick.

224
00:22:38,300 --> 00:22:41,100
And he's all alone,
except for my mother.

225
00:22:41,700 --> 00:22:45,300
I knew he was in hospital,
but I didn't realize...

226
00:22:47,400 --> 00:22:50,100
I almost never come to Montreal, so...

227
00:22:54,200 --> 00:22:56,300
Where is he now, is he still in hospital?

228
00:22:56,900 --> 00:22:59,200
Pierre, I need you... now.

229
00:22:59,500 --> 00:23:04,000
School's starting, we haven't found
a daycare, the kids are sick...

230
