You can produce oil for $7 per barrel,
and you sell for $25.

458
00:44:52,400 --> 00:44:56,900
But you want to limit your exposure
to fluctuating oil prices. How?

459
00:44:58,500 --> 00:45:01,700
No idea.
-You see me, we do a swap.

460
00:45:01,900 --> 00:45:06,200
What's that?
-A deal where my bank pays you

461
00:45:06,400 --> 00:45:08,500
a fixed price
and you pay the floating price.

462
00:45:08,700 --> 00:45:12,100
You contract to sell your oil at a fixed
price for a fixed period. In short,

463
00:45:12,300 --> 00:45:15,600
I manage financial risk.

464
00:45:15,700 --> 00:45:17,800
Are you good at what you do?

465
00:45:19,700 --> 00:45:21,700
Pretty good.

466
00:45:28,300 --> 00:45:30,900
Could you get the driver
to stop at the lake?

467
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:36,000
Probably.

468
00:45:37,500 --> 00:45:39,800
I'd like to see the lake.

469
00:46:18,900 --> 00:46:24,800
At Berkley I did my PhD alongside Locken and
Donaldson, two future Pulitzers.

470
00:46:25,100 --> 00:46:29,500
They were no better than me,
but they were American.

471
00:46:29,700 --> 00:46:35,000
Me, I came back here, I started
to teach, got married,

472
00:46:35,300 --> 00:46:37,100
And then... then nothing else.

473
00:46:37,300 --> 00:46:41,300
Your affairs kept you too busy.
-That was small time, like you said.

474
00:46:41,500 --> 00:46:44,300
No, what I lacked was extravagance.

475
00:46:44,900 --> 00:46:50,900
Basically all I ever succeded in was pathetic trysts
in poorly heated East End flats.

476
00:46:51,700 --> 00:46:56,900
I was replaced by a TA within 48 hours.
The dean neglected to say goodbye.

477
00:46:57,200 --> 00:47:01,200
The lowliest secretary
gets a cake for maternity leave.

478
00:47:06,900 --> 00:47:14,200
Ladies and gentlemen, for health reasons
I'll be unable to complete this term.

479
00:47:14,500 --> 00:47:17,300
Ms Raphaelle Metellus
will replace me.

480
00:47:18,800 --> 00:47:21,700
Does this affect our deadlines?

481
00:47:22,500 --> 00:47:25,500
No, deadlines and exam dates
remain unchanged.

482
00:47:26,500 --> 00:47:28,300
Any other questions?

483
00:47:35,400 --> 00:47:37,500
Good luck.
-Thanks.

484
00:47:42,200 --> 00:47:48,200
So, as you saw last week, the 1840
election was particularly stormy.

485
00:47:48,700 --> 00:47:50,900
The Whig party,

486
00:47:52,500 --> 00:47:57,700
then newly formed, united four
distinct constituencies

487
00:47:57,900 --> 00:48:02,200
First, the National Republicans, followers of
Adams and Clay, the party founders.

488
00:49:06,700 --> 00:49:09,000
Irina's home, I have to go out.

489
00:49:25,600 --> 00:49:27,900
Is Nathalie buying for you?

490
00:49:28,100 --> 00:49:30,100
She's a friend.

491
00:49:30,700 --> 00:49:34,500
If you're a regular,
maybe we should deal directly.

492
00:49:34,900 --> 00:49:37,000
It's only temporary.

493
00:49:37,300 --> 00:49:40,000
Everything in life is temporary.

494
00:49:40,300 --> 00:49:44,900
"you can never swim
in the same river twice," said...

495
00:49:45,400 --> 00:49:50,000
what's his face? You know...

496
00:49:52,500 --> 00:49:56,700
You can't count on Nathalie.
She'll pull a fast one on you.

497
00:49:57,400 --> 00:49:59,000
We'll see.

498
00:49:59,200 --> 00:50:02,000
You know where I live.
-Sure.

499
00:50:13,700 --> 00:50:16,900
What are you doing?
-I was waiting for you. I wanted to see you.

500
00:50:19,500 --> 00:50:23,100
You're always on my mind.
-I know, you've told me.

501
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:30,200
At night I picture you bleeding
in an alley, in shooting galleries.

502
00:50:30,400 --> 00:50:33,500
I'm always so scared.
It's unbearable.

503
00:50:34,800 --> 00:50:36,900
You imagine too much.

504
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:41,100
You know this can't go on.

505
00:50:41,400 --> 00:50:46,700
Of course I know. I know it better 
than you. You can't do anything for me.

506
00:50:49,600 --> 00:50:52,400
I know it's my fault,
that's what's killing me.

507
00:50:55,800 --> 00:50:59,400
That doesn't change anything.
I don't need this.

508
00:51:10,100 --> 00:51:12,900
You don't care much
about living, do you?

509
00:51:13,600 --> 00:51:15,500
Not really.

510
00:51:15,700 --> 00:51:20,200
I was like you at your age. Ready to
die at any time. I give a shit.

511
00:51:20,500 --> 00:51:23,500
That's why the young people
make the best martyrs.

512
00:51:23,700 --> 00:51:26,400
It's paradoxical,
but living grows on you,

513
00:51:26,600 --> 00:51:29,200
when you begin to subtract:
I've got 20 years left, 15, 10.

514
00:51:29,400 --> 00:51:33,200
When you realize it's for the last time.

515
00:51:33,500 --> 00:51:35,500
I'm buying my last car.

516
00:51:35,700 --> 00:51:38,900
This is my last trip
to Genoa, Barcelona...

517
00:51:39,100 --> 00:51:41,900
I won't live that long.
-How do you know?

518
00:51:44,300 --> 00:51:47,000
Overdoses are pretty frequent, you know.

519
00:51:47,300 --> 00:51:52,500
But you can never tell. Maybe you'll
kick it and reach a ripe old age.

520
00:51:53,200 --> 00:51:56,900
We can't decipher the past,
how can we know the future?

521
00:51:57,100 --> 00:51:59,900
No one ever knows what'll happen to them.

522
00:52:00,100 --> 00:52:02,700
Except me, now. I know.

523
00:52:03,100 --> 00:52:09,100
Are you scared? -Sure am. I don't want to
stop living. I loved life so much. You can't know how much.

524
00:52:09,600 --> 00:52:12,600
What was it you loved?
-Everything.

525
00:52:13,300 --> 00:52:18,500
Wine, books, music, women,
above all women.

526
00:52:20,100 --> 00:52:23,400
Their smell, their mouths,
the feel of their skin.

527
00:52:23,900 --> 00:52:26,200
Were there many of them?
-Yes.

528
00:52:26,400 --> 00:52:30,300
Don't they begin to seem the same?
-A bit, yes.

529
00:52:30,700 --> 00:52:33,100
But I never get tired of them.

530
00:52:33,300 --> 00:52:39,300
Still the great seducer? -No, not anymore.
With age, it's not the same thing.

531
00:52:40,800 --> 00:52:43,000
At least you can enjoy wine just as much as before.

532
00:52:43,200 --> 00:52:46,700
Unfortunately  not.
Not with my liver.

533
00:52:46,900 --> 00:52:49,600
The trips you dreamed of,
did you make them?

534
00:52:49,800 --> 00:52:52,300
Ah, in any case, nowadays there are tourists everywhere.

535
00:52:55,700 --> 00:53:00,000
It's not the present you cling on,
It's your past.

536
00:53:00,900 --> 00:53:04,900
That life is already dead.
-Perhaps.

537
00:53:59,100 --> 00:54:03,800
I expected a musty antique dealer,
not a ravishing young lady.

538
00:54:08,900 --> 00:54:11,000
I warn you, I'm no specialist.

539
00:54:11,200 --> 00:54:15,400
At one time
everyone here was Catholic.

540
00:54:15,700 --> 00:54:18,400
Like in Spain or Ireland.

541
00:54:18,900 --> 00:54:28,300
At a very precise moment in 1966, in fact the
churches suddenly emptied out, in a few months.

542
00:54:30,700 --> 00:54:34,400
A very strange phenomenon
that has yet to be explained.

543
00:54:34,900 --> 00:54:38,100
So now we don't know
what to do with this.

544
00:54:39,300 --> 00:54:44,900
The authorities would like to find
out if it has any value.

545
00:54:48,600 --> 00:54:51,000
Commercial value?
-Yes.

546
00:55:10,900 --> 00:55:14,900
Do you have any 18th-centuary
French cahlices?

547
00:55:15,200 --> 00:55:19,900
The Americans snapped them up.
There are a few examples in the museums.

548
00:55:24,100 --> 00:55:29,700
I'm sure this has great value
for people here, the collective memory.

549
00:55:32,100 --> 00:55:37,800
But is there anything that we could sell?
-On the world market?

550
00:55:42,200 --> 00:55:44,500
Honestly, I can't imagine it.

551
00:55:44,700 --> 00:55:49,100
In other words,
this is all absolutely worthless.

552
00:55:52,300 --> 00:55:54,100
I'll show you out.

553
00:56:02,300 --> 00:56:05,600
Pius XII sitting on his ass
in his gilded Vatican

554
00:56:05,800 --> 00:56:09,700
while Primo Levi was taken
to Auschwitz... That's not sad!

555
00:56:10,200 --> 00:56:13,000
It's despicable! Hideous!

556
00:56:20,600 --> 00:56:26,300
If what you say is true, and history
is a series of abominable crimes,

557
00:56:27,200 --> 00:56:30,900
then someone has to exist
who can forgive us.

558
00:56:32,800 --> 00:56:34,600
That's my belief.

559
00:56:35,700 --> 00:56:37,500
I envy you.

560
00:56:40,500 --> 00:56:43,100
If at least I'd written.

561
00:56:43,300 --> 00:56:48,200
You wrote nothing?
-A few papers here and there, nothing serious.

562
00:56:48,400 --> 00:56:50,000
What are you doing?

563
00:56:50,700 --> 00:56:53,100
What are you doing?
-It bugs me.

564
00:56:54,500 --> 00:56:56,500
What would you have written?

565
00:56:56,700 --> 00:57:00,500
<i>The Gulag Archipelago,
The Periodic Table.</i>

566
00:57:03,200 --> 00:57:06,400
Really, you think you could have done that?
-Never. -So?

567
00:57:06,900 --> 00:57:12,700
At least I'd have left a mark. We need to
succeed, even on our own terms.

568
00:57:12,900 --> 00:57:17,500
To be a able to say we did our best.
It allows us to die at peace.

569
00:57:18,400 --> 00:57:23,700
I'm a total failure.
-At least you realize it.

570
00:57:24,100 --> 00:57:27,200
So many professors are smug,
unbearable.

571
00:57:27,700 --> 00:57:32,600
I don't know your daughter,
but Sebastien's not exactly a failure.

572
00:57:33,900 --> 00:57:37,700
Not thanks to me.
-You don't know that.

573
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:44,500
We thought we'd pay a visit.
-Everyone wonders how you are.

574
00:57:44,800 --> 00:57:48,300
Not everyone, surely.
-You'd be surprised.

575
00:57:48,700 --> 00:57:52,200
That last day in class
no one seemed very moved.

576
00:57:52,400 --> 00:57:57,700
We had no idea at the time.
-Exactly. Now that you're gone...

577
00:57:57,900 --> 00:57:59,900
We see what we're missing.

578
00:58:00,400 --> 00:58:02,700
I'm touched to hear that. Sincerely.

579
00:58:08,200 --> 00:58:10,100
We should be going.

580
00:58:10,300 --> 00:58:14,500
We have a lecture by Mr Roby at 4.
-Off you go.

581
00:58:15,800 --> 00:58:18,100
Good luck.
-Thanks.

582
00:58:26,700 --> 00:58:28,800
-Don't give up.
-I won't.

583
00:58:31,700 --> 00:58:34,100
Well I never.
-Surprising.

584
00:58:34,200 --> 00:58:36,500
For illiterates, they're sweet.

585
00:58:36,700 --> 00:58:40,800
It's not their fault.
No one taught them.

586
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:54,500
At this price we'll come anytime.
-We'll see.

587
00:58:55,400 --> 00:58:57,000
I don't want it.

588
00:58:57,200 --> 00:58:59,300
We agreed.
-No, thanks.

589
00:59:02,600 --> 00:59:06,300
Do you want to split hers?

590
00:59:14,900 --> 00:59:19,400
We're getting married next summer,
at my parents' in France.

591
00:59:19,600 --> 00:59:22,100
You'll see, the chapel's lovely.

592
00:59:22,900 --> 00:59:24,800
Louise and I married on

593
00:59:25,100 --> 00:59:27,900
a grey February day in a dismal suburb.

594
00:59:28,200 --> 00:59:31,800
So we could sleep together
without our families hassling us.

595
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:34,600
I want a wedding on the Loire.

596
00:59:34,800 --> 00:59:37,500
6 months later I cheated on her.

597
00:59:37,700 --> 00:59:39,700
That was fast.
-Indeed.

598
00:59:45,900 --> 00:59:51,400
When I met Sebastien, I said: With him
it's forever, there'll be no one else.

599
00:59:51,900 --> 00:59:54,400
I hope it lasts, for your sake.

600
00:59:54,600 --> 00:59:58,700
Because, you know, love...
-No, no, no! Not "love."

601
01:00:01,300 --> 01:00:04,000
Mom and Dad
talked about nothing else. "Love."

602
01:00:04,200 --> 01:00:08,100
I love you. I love you too much.
I don't love you.

603
01:00:08,900 --> 01:00:12,200
You can't build a life
on pop-song philosophy.

604
01:00:12,400 --> 01:00:16,300
<i>Love Me Tender. Love, Love Me Not.</i>
It's ridiculous.

605
01:00:16,700 --> 01:00:19,400
My parents divorced when I was 3.

606
01:00:19,600 --> 01:00:24,400
For several years Dad continued
to come over for Sunday lunch.

607
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:28,600
Half an hour before he left,
I'd vanish.

608
01:00:28,800 --> 01:00:33,700
I'd be lying on the ground in front
of his car so he couldn't leave.

609
01:00:34,500 --> 01:00:37,300
Its out of the question that my 
kids go through that.

610
01:00:42,400 --> 01:00:49,100
So now my nocturnal pleasures are provided by
my giant-screen Toshiba at the foot of my bed.

611
01:00:49,400 --> 01:00:51,400
No more curled-up toes?

612
01:00:51,600 --> 01:00:55,400
That's over. I've seen enough ceilings.
-For ever?

613
01:00:55,600 --> 01:01:00,300
I've closed the store, laid down my weapons,
hung up my skates.

614
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:04,300
Things are much quieter between us too.
-Well, well.

615
01:01:05,700 --> 01:01:09,000
He's in Bologna all week
and I'm in Rome.

616
01:01:09,400 --> 01:01:11,300
There's the weekend, but...

617
01:01:11,600 --> 01:01:14,400
My wife falls asleep in bed
with the kids.

618
01:01:14,700 --> 01:01:17,500
Great, you can reread Tocqueville.

619
01:01:17,700 --> 01:01:20,600
That's what I did.
2000 pages on bible paper.

620
01:01:20,700 --> 01:01:24,900
He's increasingly cultivated,
and his prostate increasingly swollen.

621
01:01:25,600 --> 01:01:28,500
Sorry, I still enjoy it a lot.

622
01:01:29,500 --> 01:01:31,700
In the country
there's an old cowboy I...

623
01:01:38,600 --> 01:01:40,900
Cowboy? You're with a cowboy now?

624
01:01:41,100 --> 01:01:44,900
Yes. There's an old cowboy
I invite over to shake my bush.

625
01:01:45,200 --> 01:01:49,700
To shake your bush!
-Yes, but we had a fight.

626
01:01:50,000 --> 01:01:54,700
I'll never understand men.
All my life I date asses

627
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:58,700
who thought only of escaping
after satisfying their base needs.

628
01:01:58,900 --> 01:02:02,700
The other day, as a compliment,
I said to my cowboy:

629
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:09,400
To think we can still have sexual flings at our age.
He was incensed. He doesn't want to be a sex object,

630
01:02:09,600 --> 01:02:13,300
talks about his masculinity.
-We love that!

631
01:02:13,500 --> 01:02:18,900
Invokes father hunger goes on about exploring
his feminine side, his inner me.

632
01:02:19,200 --> 01:02:21,500
It was unbearable.

633
01:02:21,700 --> 01:02:25,300
The last thing I want is
a limp-dicked sentimentalist.

634
01:02:25,500 --> 01:02:28,400
I want to be screwed forcefully.
That's all.

635
01:02:28,600 --> 01:02:32,300
I'm sensitive
and smart enough for two.

636
01:02:32,600 --> 01:02:34,200
A rub-down?

637
01:02:34,400 --> 01:02:38,500
Would he like a rub-down? Does the
Muslim need to bow towards Mecca?

638
01:02:38,800 --> 01:02:41,600
Does the Carmelite
long for the Holy Species?

639
01:02:42,800 --> 01:02:46,700
Is this your first time here?
-Yes...

640
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:50,700
I don't know if you believe
in random acts of kindness,

641
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:54,800
but if you do,
render this sick man happy.

642
01:02:55,000 --> 01:02:57,100
Give him the mother
of all rub-downs.

643
01:02:57,400 --> 01:03:02,200
You will be repaid a hundredfold
in this life or another.

644
01:03:24,600 --> 01:03:26,800
Am I in heaven already?

645
01:03:27,200 --> 01:03:30,500
Are you my Valkyrie, my houri?

646
01:03:35,600 --> 01:03:37,100
Oh joy!

647
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:04,900
Nathalie didn't show.

648
01:04:05,200 --> 01:04:09,800
It's bad.
Your father's in withdrawal.

649
01:04:20,900 --> 01:04:23,600
Know where Nathalie is?
-No idea.

650
01:04:23,800 --> 01:04:26,900
She's disappeared.
-I warned you.

651
01:04:27,600 --> 01:04:30,700
I may come back.
-Before 11.

652
01:04:40,100 --> 01:04:42,500
I'm not supposed to do this.

653
01:05:04,600 --> 01:05:08,200
You were right.
You said not to trust you.

654
01:05:08,700 --> 01:05:10,900
Your dealer said that too.

655
01:05:12,100 --> 01:05:14,400
Wake up. We've a contract.

656
01:05:14,800 --> 01:05:18,100
What contract?
-I buy the dope, you look after Dad.

657
01:05:18,700 --> 01:05:21,900
What's with him?
-He's waiting for you.

658
01:05:22,100 --> 01:05:24,100
We're coming.

659
01:05:24,600 --> 01:05:26,700
You honor a contract!

660
01:05:26,900 --> 01:05:32,500
That's heavy, man.
-No its not "heavy." We had a deal. I'm counting on you.

661
01:05:32,900 --> 01:05:36,900
At the market... my dad...
Y'know, my dad...

662
01:05:37,600 --> 01:05:42,800
